                    %h1 Items & Armor
                :markdown
                    Item tags have many different attributes, and some may only apply to certain items. Such as the `color=""` attribute, it currently only applies to leather armor.

                    List of item names: [bukkit docs - Material](http://jd.bukkit.org/apidocs/org/bukkit/Material.html)

                        <item>Item name or id</item>
                        
                        <!-- Item attributes -->
                        slot="0"
                        name="Name String"
                        enchantment="enchantment:lvl"
                        lore="Lore String"
                        color="RRGGBB"
                        damage="0"
                        attributes="attribute:add:lvl"


                    The `slot=""` attribute specifies where the item will be placed in the inventory. [Inventory slot reference](/reference/inventory).
                    Enchantments use the bukkit [enchantment name](/reference/enchantments), the level of the enchantment is specified after a colon `:`. Multiple enchantments are separated by a semicolon `;`.

                        <item enchantment="sharpness:2">iron sword</item> <!-- A sharpness II iron sword -->
                        <item enchantment="knockback:4">280</item> <!-- A knockback IV stick -->


                    Items can be give custom names and lore with the `name=""` and `lore=""` attributes. Colors in item names or lore are specified with the grave symbol `` ` and then the minecraft [color code](/reference/formatting). You can specify multiple lines of lore using a pipe symbol `|` for line breaks.

                        <item lore="Magic Dust">331</item> <!-- Redstone dust with a fancy lore. -->
                        <item name="`6Golden Sword">gold sword</item> <!-- Gold sword with a gold/yellow name. -->
                        <item lore="`4The One and Only">stick</item> <!-- A stick with the lore colored red. -->
                        <item lore="`eWarning!|`5Does damage!">iron sword</item> <!-- A sword with 2 lines of lore. -->

                    <br/>
                    #### Armor
                    Armor slots have predefined tags to make it easier to give them to a player. They accept most of the properties of normal items.

                        <helmet>iron helmet</helmet>
                        <chestplate>diamond chestplate</chestplate>
                        <leggings>gold leggings</leggings>
                        <boots>leather boots</boots>

                    Enchanting, naming or giving armor lore works the same way as with items.

                        <boots enchantment="protection fall:1" lore="The Winged Boots of Hermes">iron boots</boots>

                    Items like leather armor are colored with the `color=""` attribute.
                    The color is represented in hexadecimal. See [Minecraft wiki - Dye Data Values](http://www.minecraftwiki.net/wiki/Dyeing#Data_values) for a list of hex colors for the different dyes.

                    `NOTE:` The hex color value is specified without the hash `#` symbol.

                        <helmet color="cd0000">leather helmet</helmet>
 
                    The `attributes=""` will allow you to set an attribute to an item or a piece of armor. Look at [Minecraft wiki - Attributes](http://minecraft.gamepedia.com/Attribute) for a list of different attributes.

                        <chestplate attributes="generic.knockbackResistance:add:1">chainmail chestplate</chestplate>
                        <item attributes="generic.knockbackResistance:add:1">diamond spade</item>
                        <item attributes="generic.knockbackResistance:add:1;generic.movementSpeed:add:2">diamond spade</item>
                        <leggings attributes="generic.maxHealth:add:-6">iron leggings</leggings> <!-- Unit of maxHealth is in half-hearts -->

                    `NOTE:` Negative attribute values are allowed; however, sometimes don't work as expected.
